 volume is to understand how children and youth encounter, move through, or are outside of a range of legal processes, including border enforcement, immigration detention, federal custody, courts, and state processes of categorization. Even if young people do not directly interact with state immigration systems-because they are U.S. citizens or have avoided detention-they are nonetheless deeply affected by the reach of the government in its many forms.Contributors privilege the voices and everyday experiences of immigrant children and youth themselves. By combining different perspectives from advocates, service providers, attorneys, researchers, and young immigrants, the volume presents rich accounts that can contribute to informed debates and policy reforms. Illegal Encounters sheds light on the unique ways in which policies, laws, and legal categories shape so much of daily life for young immigrants. The book makes visible the burdens, hopes, and potential of a population of young people and their families who have been largely hidden from public view and are currently under siege, following their movement through complicated immigration systems and institutions in the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCentral AmericansxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 0aCentral Americans-Legal status, laws, etc.-United States. 0aDeportationzUnited States. 0aDeportation-United States. 0aIllegal alien children-Government policy-United States. 0aIllegal alien children-United States-Social conditions. 0aIllegal immigrationxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aIllegal immigrationzUnited States. 0aJuvenile detentionzUnited States. 0aJuvenile detention-United States. 0aMexicansxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 0aMexicans-Legal status, laws, etc.-United States. 0aNoncitizen childrenx